#OceanXplorer in the #Arctic update: Repost from @eerrp
•
We ventured out to survey freshly exposed glacier wall on one of OceanXplorer's tenders. Beautiful cascading waterfalls plunged over striated lines of blue and white ice that almost looked like granite, compressed by accumulation over thousands of years. Along the waterline we could spot dozens of small caves and undercuts from underice passageways that were begging for exploration but forbidding from their fragility. In the several hours we were there we watched many tons of ice break off into the water in a massive roar and churn the sea as if it were boiling. Birds have learned to wait by the ice edge for these events as the movement seems to cause food from the bottom to be mixed with the surface. Because I have no baseline for normal in such a foreign place, it is hard to understand the context of seeing so much mass that has been growing and traveling for so long go through such dramatic change so quickly. Regardless of that, I tried to take in the melancholy astonishment of realizing that we were certainly the first and probably the last ship to explore this particular glacial bay of caves and waterfalls while it lasts. The hydrologist onboard said the area we sailed into was more then a kilometer further inland then last year and would likely continue at a similar pace next year as well.

